    def Execute(libName: str, className: str, methodName: str, inputArgs: List[any]) -> any:
        """
         Invokes a method in a library.
                
                Currently supported library types
                include a Java jar or class file, a Common Language Runtime (.NET) dll, a C++ shared library, or a Python script.
                
                The input arguments should not contain KF attributes vector, point and frame
                Instead it should be passed as double[3], double[3] and double[16] respectively.
                
                For C++ no class methods may be invoked.
                If the the entry point name is ufusr, the signature of that function must be: 
                "ufusr( char parm, int returnCode, int rlen )"
                
                If the entry point's name is anything other than ufusr, the signature of the function must be following format, where ENTRY_POINT is a function name other than ufusr:
                void ENTRY_POINT(std::vectorNXVariant variants, NXVariant &amp; retVal)
                
                For Python, only class bound static methods and global functions can be invoked.
                Do not use this method for other Python methods since the behavior is undefined.
                
                For .NET, it is strongly recommended that you use something other than Main for methodName parameter. 
                If Main is used, then note that the return argument type must either be void or int. No other return types will work.
                
                Allowable types to pass as Variant arguments are integers, double, booleans, NXOpen.TaggedObject, 
                and strings (NXString for C++).  Additionally, you can have arrays (mapped to the correct language type) of Variants.  However,
                the arrays must homogeneous.  That is cannot have an array with both integers and strings.  However, you can have two arrays, one array of integers
                and another array of strings.  And then pass in this array of arrays as input arguments.  The output argument is limited single array though.
                
                See the SessionExecute example for more details of how this works.
                
                 
         Returns result (any):  Return argument for managed method .
        """
        pass
